lessons.theory:
## Two key tools

### `std::meta::data_member_spec`

```cpp
consteval std::meta::info
data_member_spec(std::meta::info type_reflection,
                 data_member_options options = {});
```

Creates a **field descriptor** — an object of type `std::meta::info` describing a future non-static data member. Key `options` fields:

| Option | Type | Meaning |
|--------|------|---------|
| `name` | `std::string_view` | Field name; required for named fields |
| `alignment` | `size_t` | Explicit alignment (optional) |
| `width` | `size_t` | Bit-field width (optional) |
| `no_unique_address` | `bool` | `[[no_unique_address]]` (optional) |

The function is `consteval`, meaning it can only be called in a compile-time context.

### `std::meta::define_aggregate`

```cpp
consteval std::meta::info
define_aggregate(std::meta::info class_reflection,
                 /* range of */ std::meta::info members);
```

Takes a reflection of an **incomplete** (forward-declared) type and a range of field descriptors, and **defines** that type as an aggregate-struct with the given fields.

> **Important:** In P2996R8, `define_class` was renamed to `define_aggregate`. On clang_bb_p2996 the old name triggers a deprecation warning — use `define_aggregate`.

## Key constraint: the "plainly constant-evaluated" context

`define_aggregate` performs a **declaration injection** into the program — a fundamentally different operation from regular computations. The compiler requires the call to originate from a "plainly constant-evaluated" context.

The single reliably working approach is a **namespace-scope `consteval { }` block**:

```cpp
struct MyPoint;   // forward declaration

consteval {       // ← namespace-scope consteval block
    std::meta::define_aggregate(^^MyPoint, {
        std::meta::data_member_spec(^^float, {.name = "x"}),
        std::meta::data_member_spec(^^float, {.name = "y"})
    });
}

// MyPoint is now a complete type: struct MyPoint { float x; float y; };
```

**Why not a `consteval` function?** Calling a `consteval` function via a `constexpr` variable is not a "plainly constant-evaluated" context per the current specification; the compiler will emit the error "cannot produce an injected declaration from a non-plainly constant-evaluated context".

## Pattern: programmatic field generation

Inside a `consteval { }` block you can use any compile-time algorithms — `std::vector`, loops, conditionals:

```cpp
struct Generated;

consteval {
    std::vector<std::meta::info> fields;
    for (char c : {'x', 'y', 'z'}) {
        fields.push_back(
            std::meta::data_member_spec(^^double, {.name = std::string(1, c)})
        );
    }
    std::meta::define_aggregate(^^Generated, fields);
}
```

## Pattern: type transformation

By reflecting an existing type you can systematically transform its fields. Example — wrapping every field in `std::optional`:

```cpp
struct Source { int a; float b; };
struct Patch;

consteval {
    std::vector<std::meta::info> fields;
    for (auto m : std::meta::nonstatic_data_members_of(
                      ^^Source, std::meta::access_context::unchecked())) {
        auto opt_type = std::meta::substitute(
            ^^std::optional, {std::meta::type_of(m)});
        fields.push_back(
            std::meta::data_member_spec(opt_type,
                {.name = std::meta::identifier_of(m)}));
    }
    std::meta::define_aggregate(^^Patch, fields);
}
// Patch is equivalent to: struct Patch { std::optional<int> a; std::optional<float> b; };
```

## Important details

- **Forward declaration is mandatory**: the type must be declared (`struct Foo;`) before `define_aggregate` defines it.
- **Cannot redefine**: if the type is already complete, `define_aggregate` will result in a compile error.
- **`nonstatic_data_members_of` requires `access_context`**: without it you get a deprecation warning (P2996R10 made this argument mandatory). Use `std::meta::access_context::unchecked()`.
- **`std::meta::substitute`** builds a reflection of a template specialization: `substitute(^^std::optional, {^^int})` → reflection of `std::optional<int>`.

